'''Charles James Campbell''' (November 6, 1819 &ndash; April 17, 1906) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]]-born merchant and political figure in [[Nova Scotia]], Canada. He represented [[Victoria (Nova Scotia electoral district)|Victoria]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] from 1874 to 1875, from 1876 to 1878 and from 1882 to 1887 as a [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member.<ref name="parl">{{Canadian Parliament links|ID=5357 |nolist=yes}}</ref>

He was born on the [[Isle of Skye]],<ref name="parl"/> the son of John Campbell and Isabella McRae, and came to Nova Scotia in 1831. In 1843, Campbell married Eliza Jane Ingraham. He owned the New Campbell Coal Mines. He was named a [[justice of the peace]] for [[Cape Breton County, Nova Scotia|Cape Breton County]] in 1851 and county coroner in 1857. Campbell was also lieutenant-colonel for the county militia,<ref name="gemmill"/> served as a chairman of the county board of health, was a school trustee and served on the province's board of agriculture.<ref>[http://www.canadiana.org/ECO/mtq?doc=08546 ''The Canadian biographical dictionary and portrait gallery of eminent and self-made men ...'' (1881)]</ref>

Campbell represented [[Victoria (Nova Scotia provincial electoral district)|Victoria County]] in the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] from 1853 to 1859, from 1863 to 1867 and from 1871 to 1873. He was also elected to the provincial assembly in 1851 and 1860 but was unseated after those elections were appealed. He served as a member of the province's Executive Council from 1856 to 1859.<ref name="gemmill">[http://www.canadiana.org/ECO/mtq?doc=32957 ''The Canadian parliamentary companion, 1883'', JA Gemmill]</ref> In 1873, he was named to the province's [[Legislative Council of Nova Scotia|Legislative Council]] and he served until 1874, when he was elected to the House of Commons. His election was subsequently overturned the following year. Campbell was an unsuccessful candidate for the House of Commons in 1873, 1875, 1878 and 1887.<ref name="parl"/>

Campbell died in North Sydney at the age of 86.<ref name="johnson">{{cite book |title=The Canadian Directory of Parliament 1867-1967 |last=Johnson |first=J.K. |year=1968 |publisher=Public Archives of Canada}}</ref>

