'''Chase, the son of Ioube''' ({{lang-el|Χασὲ υἱὸς τοῦ Ἰούβη}}), originally '''Hasan ibn Ayyub''', was a senior [[Byzantine]] official of [[Arabs|Arab]] origin.

== Biography ==
Chase, a [[Hellenized]] form of the Arabic name "Hasan", is mentioned by the ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'', a work compiled in the middle of the 10th century by [[Constantine VII Porphyrogennetos]], and the chronicles of [[Theophanes Continuatus]] and [[Georgius Monachus]].{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Chase (#21238)}} Along with his younger brother, who received the Christian name [[Niketas (son of Ioube)|Niketas]] on his [[baptism]], he was reportedly a slave of the ''[[patrikios]]'' [[Damian (parakoimomenos)|Damian]], the ''[[parakoimomenos]]'' of Emperor [[Michael III]] ({{reign|842|867}}), implying that they had been captured as prisoners of war during a [[Arab–Byzantine wars|conflict with the Arabs]] around the middle of the 9th century or shortly after. It is unclear whether they came alone or with their father Ioube (Ἰούβη, Hellenized form of Ayyub{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Iube (#23571)}}); it is possible that they came to Byzantium as children, and that Niketas was even born there. Unlike his brother, who converted to Christianity, Chase remained a Muslim throughout his life.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Chase (#21238)}}

Constantine VII asserts that during the reign of his uncle [[Alexander (emperor)|Alexander]] ({{reign|912|913}}), Chase was one of his closest confidantes. Constantine VII further accuses him of having a negative influence on the emperor.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Chase (#21238)}} According to the chroniclers, he held a fiscal position in the [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of [[Hellas (theme)|Hellas]] thereafter. He became quickly hated by the local inhabitants due to his incessant demands, until he was [[stoning|stoned]] to death before the altar of a church (most likely the converted [[Parthenon]]) in [[Athens]]. As he was a Muslim, he may have tried to seek sanctuary there, or otherwise his entering of the church may have outraged the congregation leading to his murder. His death took place probably in 915.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Chase (#21238)}}

The ''illoustrios'' [[John Ioubes]] later in the century was possibly a descendant or otherwise a relative.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Iube (#23571)}}

