{{Infobox musical artist | name =John Panozzo | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_name = John Anthony Panozzo | birth_date = {{birth date|1948|09|20}} | birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1996|7|16|1948|9|20}} | death_place = Chicago | occupation = Musician | instrument = [[Drum kit|Drums]] | genre = [[Progressive rock]], [[rock music|rock]], [[hard rock]] | label = | associated_acts = [[Styx (band)|Styx]] | years_active = 1956–1996 }}
'''John Anthony Panozzo''' (September 20, 1948 – July 16, 1996) was an American drummer best known for his work with rock band [[Styx (band)|Styx]].
==Early life and career== Panozzo grew up in the [[Roseland, Chicago|Roseland]] neighborhood, the [[South Side, Chicago|south side]] of [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]], with his [[fraternal twin]] brother, [[Chuck Panozzo|Chuck]] (born 90 minutes apart). At age 7, the twins took musical lessons from their uncle in which John took an interest in drums and percussion. They attended Catholic school and eventually they were part of a three-piece band in which John played drums and Chuck played guitar. They would play weddings at age 12 and were paid $15 apiece.
Then, in 1961, John, Chuck, and their neighbor, [[Dennis DeYoung]], formed a band called The Tradewinds in which John played drums, Chuck played guitar, and Dennis played the [[accordion]] and sang. They played local gigs at bars and began gaining popularity as a garage band on the city's South Side. In 1968, Chuck switched to [[bass guitar|bass]] and they added guitarists/vocalists [[James Young (American musician)|James "J.Y." Young]] and [[John Curulewski]], changing their name to TW4.<ref name=clark>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Dick|title=Styx and stones...|newspaper=[[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|Times-News]]|date=March 29, 1983}}</ref> The band signed to [[Wooden Nickel Records]] and changed their name to [[Styx (band)|Styx]].
==Illness and death== Years of [[alcoholism|excessive drinking]] began to take a toll on his [[liver]]. In the mid-1990s, as Styx was about to embark on its first tour with the classic line-up since 1983, John fell seriously ill and began battling [[cirrhosis]] of the liver, eventually dying of [[gastrointestinal]] hemorrhaging and cirrhosis in [[Chicago]]; he was 47 years old.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=John Panozzo - Styx Drummer|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|date=July 16, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=John Panozzo, 47, 70's Rock Drummer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/18/arts/john-panozzo-47-70-s-rock-drummer.html|accessdate=23 September 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 18, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Perrone|first=Pierre|title=Obituary: John Panozzo|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-john-panozzo-1329507.html|accessdate=23 September 2013|newspaper=The Independent|date=20 July 1996}}</ref><ref>http://articles.latimes.com/1996-07-18/news/mn-25369_1_john-panozzo</ref>
==Tribute== The band dedicated their 1996 ''Return to Paradise'' tour to him, and [[Tommy Shaw]], who had earlier replaced Curulewski, wrote the song "Dear John" as the band's final tribute to their drummer and friend.
==Gear== Panozzo used [[Premier drums]] during the band's early years then switched to [[Tama drums]] by late 1978. He also played [[Zildjian cymbals]].
