{{Use American English|date=September 2014}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}

In Pennsylvania, there are a number of murder victims, in the category of [[unidentified decedent]]s, whose identities have yet to be found. In most of these cases, their murderer or murderers have also gone undiscovered.

[[File:Boy in the Box 1957 Recon 001C.jpg|thumb|The [[Boy in the Box (Philadelphia)|Boy in the Box]] is perhaps the most prominent case in Pennsylvania]]

== Boy in the Box ==
{{Main|Boy in the Box (Philadelphia)}}

A young boy found in 1957. He died from severe blunt force trauma visible across his body.<ref>{{cite web |title = The Boy in the Box Mystery |url = http://americasunknownchild.net/ |work = americasunknownchild.net |accessdate = June 26, 2013 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130518231141/http://americasunknownchild.net/ |archivedate = May 18, 2013 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Beth Doe ==
{{anchor|Beth Doe}}
{{Main|Beth Doe}}

A young, pregnant woman who was found murdered and dismembered in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |title = Jane Doe 1976 |url = http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1104191/1#poster |website = missingkids.org |publisher = [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]] |accessdate = July 31, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160311075818/http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1104191/1#poster |archivedate = March 11, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Jefferson County John Doe (1986) ==
{{anchor|Jefferson County John Doe (1986)}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/3882 Digital reconstruction]
}}

The skeleton of a man aged twenty-five to forty was discovered on July 25, 1986, in Washington Township, Jefferson County, Pennsylvania, near a strip mine. He was determined to be white, although he may have had Asian heritage. His skull was found several feet away from the rest of the body and had wire around the neck area, which indicated he was strangled.<ref>{{cite web |title = NamUs UP # 6574 |url = https://identifyus.org/cases/6574 |website = identifyus.org |publisher = [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] |accessdate = February 17, 2015 |date = January 19, 2010 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150217165624/https://identifyus.org/cases/6574 |archivedate = February 17, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The right hand was never recovered and the fingers on the left were also missing. It appeared that the killer or killers had attempted to prevent his identification by doing this as well as burning the man's clothing on top of the head. He had light brown hair and was estimated to be around five feet eight inches tall at around 170 to 180 pounds at the time of death.<ref>{{cite web |title = Case File 176UMPA |url = http://doenetwork.org/cases/176umpa.html |website = doenetwork.org |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = February 17, 2015 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150810071657/http://doenetwork.org/cases/176umpa.html |archivedate = August 10, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Perry County Jane Doe ==
{{Main|Perry County Jane Doe}}

A female whose body was found in 1979. The cause of this person's death is unknown, but is ruled as suspicious.<ref>{{cite web |title = Case File 11UFPA |url = http://doenetwork.org/cases/11ufpa.html |website = doenetwork.org |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = August 24, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141102015811/http://doenetwork.org/cases/11ufpa.html |archivedate = November 2, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>
{{anchor|Penny Doe}}

== Penny Doe ==

[[File:Clarion County, Pennsylvania Jane Doe facial reconstruction.jpg|thumb|left|Artist's rendering of "Penny Doe"]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/14624 Digital 3D reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://www.hellbeasts.com/images/6580new_recon.jpg Digital reconstruction]
| image3 = [http://www.hellbeasts.com/images/clarion_jane_doe1.jpg 3D reconstruction]
}}

A female's body found in [[Monroe, Pennsylvania|Monroe]], [[Clarion County, Pennsylvania]], on July 22, 1990, the death blow being [[blunt-force trauma]] to the head. Additionally, the right leg was broken. She was between fifteen and twenty-two (although some sources report her being as old as forty). She had very healthy teeth and had long brown hair and had one baby tooth still in place on the top set of teeth. The victim wore no [[Brassiere|bra]], shoes or socks, which may have been taken by the killer. In each pocket of the woman's jeans was a single [[penny]], which led to her nickname. The other clothing worn was a vest over a black shirt reading "Stop Light of California". She was not believed to have come from the area where she was discovered.<ref name="Case File 246UFPA">{{cite web |title = Case File 246UFPA |url = http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/246ufpa.html |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = April 21, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140422233041/http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/246ufpa.html |archivedate = April 22, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="Penny Doe">{{cite web |title = Penny Doe |url = http://pennsylvaniamissing.com/246ufpaclarioncountyjd.html |publisher = Pennsylvania Missing Persons and Unidentified Victims |accessdate = April 21, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140422232333/http://pennsylvaniamissing.com/246ufpaclarioncountyjd.html |archivedate = April 22, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="NamUs UP# 6580">{{cite web |title = NamUs UP# 6580 |url = https://identifyus.org/cases/6580 |publisher = NamUS.org |accessdate = April 21, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140422234245/https://identifyus.org/cases/6580 |archivedate = April 22, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="Clarion County Jane Doe">{{cite web |title = Clarion County Jane Doe |url = http://www.hellbeasts.com/?p=6536 |accessdate = April 21, 2014 |date = March 23, 2013 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140409081315/http://www.hellbeasts.com/?p=6536 |archivedate = April 9, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Luzerne County Jane Doe ==
{{anchor|Luzerne County Jane Doe}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/127UFPA.jpg 3D reconstruction]
}}

A female skeleton was found at the edge of a strip mine on December 20, 1994, near Sugarloaf, [[Luzerne County, Pennsylvania|Luzerne County]], [[Pennsylvania]]. The remains had been left on the surface of the ground, and were estimated to have been at the location for up to two years. Despite the cause of death not being apparent upon examination, the case is being investigated as a homicide. The woman was between 34 and 47 years old at the time of death, and between at 5 feet 1 to 5 feet 4 inches in height. With the body, a yellow shirt, reading "kiss my ass, I'm on vacation," women's underwear, sweatpants and boy's shoes were found. She had borne at least one child, and likely suffered from back pain and may have walked with a limp when alive.<ref name="Case File 127UFPA">{{cite web |title = Case File 127UFPA |url = http://doenetwork.org/cases/127ufpa.html |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = July 26, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141104165118/http://doenetwork.org/cases/127ufpa.html |archivedate = November 4, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> She also had a significant number of missing teeth, and a fragment of metal unrelated to dental work was found in her jaw.<ref>{{cite web |title = Luzerne Pennsylvania Jane Doe December 1994 |url = http://www.canyouidentifyme.org/LuzernePennsylvaniaJaneDoeDecember1994 |website = canyouidentifyme.org |accessdate = July 26, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140806135445/http://www.canyouidentifyme.org/LuzernePennsylvaniaJaneDoeDecember1994 |archivedate = August 6, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Chester County Jane Doe ==
{{anchor|Chester County Jane Doe}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/147UFPA1.jpg Digital reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/147UFPA.jpg 3D reconstruction]
| image3 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/34754 Digital reconstruction]
}}

On July 11, 1995 the dismembered remains of a female aged seventeen to forty were found in East Caln Township, Chester County, Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web |title = NamUs UP 13616 |url = https://identifyus.org/cases/13616 |website = identifyus.org |publisher = [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] |accessdate = October 25, 2016 |date = March 4, 2015 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161026081606/https://identifyus.org/cases/13616 |archivedate = October 26, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The torso was discovered first, wrapped in bedding and wax and placed into a reddish-colored suitcase, later traced to [[Kmart]]. Wire and tape were used to fasten the suitcase, which was disposed of near a river inside of a garbage bag.<ref>{{cite web |last1 = Bishop |first1 = Alex |title = Unsolved Murder Spotlight: The East Caln Township Jane Doe |url = http://www.crimelibrary.com/blog/2013/05/17/unsolved-murder-spotlight-the-east-caln-township-jane-doe/index.html |website = crimelibrary.com |publisher = Crime Library |accessdate = February 4, 2015 |date = May 17, 2013 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150204222414/http://www.crimelibrary.com/blog/2013/05/17/unsolved-murder-spotlight-the-east-caln-township-jane-doe/index.html |archivedate = February 4, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The young woman had been subjected to some violence, as she had bruises on her body. She had also consumed alcohol although not enough to intoxicate her. Her age was estimated to be between seventeen and twenty-five, although other reports state she was between eighteen and forty. The female was deceased for several days, up to one week, prior to the discovery. She may have been Hispanic with a light complexion, but otherwise appeared to be white. The victim had brown hair and eyes, was approximately four feet eleven to five feet three inches and weighed between 120 and 140 pounds. Her legs were not found until January 29 of the following year in Cores Creek State Park, which had been disposed of in trash bags. The legs were not genetically tested to match the body but did, however, fit into the other parts of the remains. Other bags were found at the scene containing various amounts of women's clothing.<ref>{{cite web |title = Case File 147UFPA |url = http://doenetwork.org/cases/147ufpa.html |website = doenetwork.org |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = February 4, 2015 |date = November 13, 2011 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150325091725/http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/147ufpa.html |archivedate = March 25, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The case was featured on ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'' in 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Hawkes |first1 = Jeff |title = Police seek help in solving 1995 case of dismembered woman found in Chester County creek |url = http://www.lancasteronline.com/news/local/police-seek-help-in-solving-case-of-dismembered-woman-found/article_ce0038d2-2f15-11e5-8071-2f28a79d67fd.html?mode=jqm |accessdate = July 23, 2015 |work = Lancaster Online |date = July 20, 2015 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171215093123/http://lancasteronline.com/news/local/police-seek-help-in-solving-case-of-dismembered-woman-found/article_ce0038d2-2f15-11e5-8071-2f28a79d67fd.html?mode=jqm |archivedate = December 15, 2017 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Philadelphia County John Doe (1995) ==
{{anchor|Philadelphia County John Doe (1995)}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184254c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/7211 Sketch]
}}

On October 28, 1995, the body of an African-American male aged sixteen to nineteen was found in Fairmount Park in Philadelphia, Philadelphia County, Pennsylvania. He had been shot twice in the head, and had been dead for approximately three days prior to being found. His black hair was styled in cornrows and there was a scar on his right arm. He had brown eyes; he was five feet eleven inches tall and weighed 163 pounds. He wore a red tee shirt, a gray hooded pullover Sergio Tacchin jacket, boxer shorts, a black belt decorated with medallions and black high-top [[Reebok]] shoes.<ref>{{cite web |title = Case File 1008UMPA |url = http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/1008umpa.html |website = doenetwork.org |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = November 22, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150412070019/http://doenetwork.org/cases/1008umpa.html |archivedate = April 12, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Both his tee shirt and underwear were made by the [[Fruit of the Loom]] company. His teeth were well cared for, although no signs of any dental treatment were found.<ref>{{cite web |title = John Doe 1995 |url = http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184254/1#poster |website = missingkids.org |publisher = [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]] |accessdate = November 22, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160311074307/http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184254/1#poster |archivedate = March 11, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = NamUs UP # 7295 |url = https://identifyus.org/cases/7295 |website = identifyus.org |publisher = [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] |accessdate = November 22, 2014 |date = June 19, 2010 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160311093831/https://identifyus.org/cases/7295 |archivedate = March 11, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Somerset County John Doe ==
{{anchor|Somerset County John Doe}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/170UMPA1.jpg 3D reconstruction]
}}

The body of a thirty- to fifty-year-old man was found on November 3, 1995 (although he likely died in 1994) in [[Somerset County, Pennsylvania|Somerset County]], [[Pennsylvania]], close to the border of [[Maryland]]. He had been shot twice in the head, likely around a year before the remains were found. He had possibly been fairly well-to-do, as the body was dressed in a pair of "Genuine Country Road" brand pants that cost around $200 when new, and he had an expensive partial dental plate replacing missing teeth. He was approximately 5 feet 6 to 5 feet 10 inches in height and weighed between 150 and 170 pounds. Despite multiple facial reconstructions, identification has thus far been unsuccessful.<ref name="Case File 170UMPA">{{cite web |url = http://doenetwork.org/cases/170umpa.html |title = Case File 170UMPA |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = June 2, 2014 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150810071959/http://doenetwork.org/cases/170umpa.html |archivedate = August 10, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Baby Allison ==
{{anchor|Baby Allison}}

In Strasburg Township, Lancaster County, Pennsylvania, the body of a newborn girl was found concealed with a plastic bag in a burn barrel on the afternoon of December 31, 2003.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Barton |first1 = Greg |title = Solving Baby Allison’s Murder |url = http://www.wdac.com/solving-baby-allisons-murder/ |accessdate = January 25, 2015 |work = WDAC |date = December 31, 2013 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150217175745/http://www.wdac.com/solving-baby-allisons-murder/ |archivedate = February 17, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The baby had been born alive and then had her throat cut and her umbilical cord was not removed from her body. She was determined to be white and to not have been of incestuous ancestry. There was also a slim possibility that she was from the Amish settlement she was located in, as genetic testing indicated.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Smart |first1 = Gill |title = Killing of Baby Allison |url = http://lancasteronline.com/news/killing-of-baby-allison/article_f98dce12-d484-5105-a46a-c1e60c0a2b51.html |accessdate = January 25, 2015 |work = Lancaster Online |date = December 30, 2013 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160904151511/http://lancasteronline.com/news/killing-of-baby-allison/article_f98dce12-d484-5105-a46a-c1e60c0a2b51.html |archivedate = September 4, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> It is presumed that the baby's mother was under twenty years old and may have been native to the area, although it is possible that she was not. A local gas station may have contained evidence from the child's birth, although it is not certain if it is related to the case.<ref>{{cite web |title = Baby Allison |url = http://pennsylvaniamissing.com/babyallison.html |website = pennsylvaniamissing.com |publisher = Pennsylvania State Troopers |accessdate = January 25, 2015 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150217180350/http://pennsylvaniamissing.com/babyallison.html |archivedate = February 17, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

== Indiana County Jane Doe ==
{{anchor|Indiana County Jane Doe}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/3852 Sketch]
| image2 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/3908 Profile]
}}

A black female with Hispanic characteristics was discovered in a wooded area on December 29, 2008, in Rochester Mills, Indiana County, Pennsylvania. She had been murdered years before, possibly between 1993 and 2003. She had been shot in the back of her head and was later dismembered with a saw, as evidence on the bones suggested.<ref>{{cite web |title = NamUs UP # 5063 |url = https://identifyus.org/cases/5063 |website = identifyus.org |publisher = [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] |accessdate = March 4, 2015 |date = April 14, 2009 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402090207/https://identifyus.org/cases/5063 |archivedate = April 2, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The victim was found with a pair of possibly gray shorts that had elastic in their waistline. The woman was estimated to be between thirty and forty years old at the time of death and was between four feet nine inches and five feet nine inches tall. Because of the state of her body, the weight was not possible to determine or estimate. The Jane Doe had a partial denture on the top set of her teeth and her hands and feet were not recovered.<ref>{{cite web |title = Case File 768UFPA |url = http://doenetwork.org/cases/768ufpa.html |website = doenetwork.org |publisher = [[The Doe Network]] |accessdate = March 4, 2015 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615104142/http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/768ufpa.html |archivedate = June 15, 2015 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

